Aim:
To write a C++ class template that works for different data types.

Algorithm:
Start program.
Define a class template using template <class T>.
Define constructor and member functions inside the class.
Create objects of different data types.
Display results.
End program.

Program:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

template <class T>
class Sample {
    T a, b;
public:
    Sample(T x, T y) {
        a = x;
        b = y;
    }

    T add() {
        return a + b;
    }
};

int main() {
    Sample<int> s1(10, 20);
    Sample<float> s2(2.5, 3.7);

    cout << "Integer Addition: " << s1.add() << endl;
    cout << "Float Addition: " << s2.add() << endl;

    return 0;
}

Output:
Integer Addition: 30
Float Addition: 6.2

Result:
Class templates were successfully demonstrated using different data types.

